English Summary

Armenia: Russias Gold Hub - In 2024 88 percent of Russian gold exports passed through Armenia

In recent years, the global gold trade has undergone significant changes, with Armenia emerging as a key player in the redistribution of Russian gold exports. Following sanctions imposed on Russia in 2022, Armenia has become the primary destination for Russian gold, with 88.4% of Russias gold exports passing through Armenia in the first quarter of 2024. This shift has led to a dramatic increase in Armenias overall export figures, with gold re-exports accounting for approximately 76% of Armenias total exports in early 2024. The surge in gold trade has masked weaknesses in other sectors of Armenias economy, as exports of traditional goods have declined.

The analysis also reveals significant discrepancies in Armenias gold trade data, particularly in recent months. Notably, in December 2023, official statistics indicate that 192 tons of gold entered Armenia at an unprecedented low price of $2.41 per gram, far below any reasonable market rate. These anomalies raise critical questions about data integrity, valuation methods, trade practices, regulatory oversight, and the broader economic implications for Armenia. As Armenias role in the global gold trade continues to evolve, it will be crucial to monitor how this impacts the countrys economic indicators and international financial relationships, while addressing the need for improved data transparency and further investigation into these trade patterns.
